text: Your Wednesday Evening BriefingHere’s what you need to know at the end of the day.
Listen to ‘The Daily’Quarantine on a college campus.
The ‘Dealbook’ NewsletterJPMorgan sends workers home.

Trump Again Scorns Science on Vaccine and MasksPresident Trump slapped down Dr. Robert Redfield, the C.D.C. chief, saying his emphasis on masks and his projected vaccine timeline were wrong.It was perhaps the starkest example of Mr. Trump rejecting the advice of public health officials and the facts they provide. Here’s the latest.
Big Ten Will Play Football in 2020, Reversing DecisionLeaders of Big Ten universities faced pressure from coaches, players and fans since announcing that the conference would not compete until 2021.
The Federal Reserve will keep interest rates near zero until at least 2023, as it tries to revive the economy.

Hurricane Sally Floods Hundreds of Homes in FloridaFloodwaters rushed through parts of Alabama and Florida, turning roads to rivers and submerging cars as the storm made landfall.Surging water in Pensacola, Fla., slammed a barge into a section of a bridge that was under construction, destroying part of it. Here’s the latest.
Climate change likely made the storm more dangerous by slowing it down and feeding it more moisture.
Blazes Scorch Habitats for Endangered SpeciesThe fast-moving fires in the Western U.S. have incinerated native habitats that may take years to recover, if they recover at all. Follow updates here.
California is pushing insurers to cut rates, but experts warn it could backfire.

Barr Told Prosecutors to Consider Sedition Charges for Protest ViolenceAttorney General William Barr was also said to have asked about bringing charges against the mayor of Seattle for allowing a police-free protest zone.
Liu Zengyan jumped from a window to escape an assault by her then husband. Her case has set off a nationwide debate in China.
